result.execSummary:
The defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Felon Possess Firearm, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(2)(a).
  • 1st-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Use Dangerous Weapon (Felony 5+ Yrs)], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. (AM)  Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in court with attorney Peter J. Kovac.  Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in custody.  Marissa Luz Santiago appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court finds State has complied with victim notification.  Statements made as to sentencing.  Due to the lateness of the hour, Court orders sentencing adjourned to 1:15pm. 

(PM)  Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in court with attorney Peter J. Kovac.  Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in custody.  Denis Stingl for Marissa Luz Santiago appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court hears additional sentencing arguments of defense.  Defendant addresses the Court. 
    
AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 5 YEARS CONSECUTIVE TO COUNT 4, with credit for 320 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS.  
AS TO COUNT 4: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS CONSECUTIVE TO COUNT 1; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  
The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is not eligible for the "Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program".

Court sets restitution at $0.  Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.  Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs and surcharges.  As to all costs and surcharges, Court orders DOC shall collect up to 25% of prison funds.  Remaining balance to be paid during the period of extended supervision.  Unpaid amount to covert to a civil judgment.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in court with attorney Peter J. Kovac.  Defendant Alugdah Mukkery Brown in custody. Marissa Santiago appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Matter is scheduled for status conference today.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY as to COUNTS 1 & 4. On motion of the State, Court orders COUNTS 2 & 3 dismissed and read-in. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms and body armor. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible. Court orders defendant REMANDED pending sentencing date.  PER JUDGE ROSA, MATTER TO REMAIN ASSIGNED TO BR. 35.
